In [42]:
import sklearn.cluster as cluster
In [43]:
K=range(1,12)
wss=[]

for k in K:
    kmeans=cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=k,init='k-means++')
    kmeans=kmeans.fit(Data1)
    wss_iter=kmeans.inertia_
    wss.append(wss_iter)

STEP 5 (conclusion)

CONCLUSION

Write a brief conclusion summarizing your results and how K-Means and Hierarchical clustering differed.

The brief conclusion summarizing

K Means clustering can handle large amounts of data better than hierarchical clustering.
In K means clustering, we must first determine the number of clusters to be produced, which might be challenging to decide. Unlike hierarchical clustering, which automatically forms data into a tree shape form (dendrogram), we can select which trees are relevant.

QUESTIONS

1. Briefly explain how both k-means and hierarchical clustering work along with their advantages/disadvantages if any
2. Give an example of where you could use hierarchical clustering or k-means

The most fundamental difference is where to use K means and Hierarchical clustering based on Scalability and Flexibility. Hierarchical is Flexible but can not be used on extensive data. K means is scalable but cannot use for flexible data. It would be best not to use hierarchical clustering for large datasets, and Hierarchical clustering is generally applicable to a small data set. When dealing with massive data sets, K means is quite beneficial. On the other hand, the K means is exclusively relevant to numeric data. When it comes to variety, hierarchical clustering is the apparent victor. It doesn't even have to be a distance; any measure, including similarity functions, may be employed simply by preferring high to low values.
